Y1  - 2000
TI  - Endophytic colonization and Æeld responses of hybrid spruce seedlings after inoculation with plant growth-promoting rhizobacteria
AB  - Bacterial colonization and growth responses of hybrid spruce (Picea glauca engelmannii) seedlings after inoculation with plant growth-promoting rhizobacteria (PGPR) were evaluated in controlled environment and Æeld assays. Six antibioticresistant bacterial strains belonging to the genera Bacillus and Pseudomonas were used as inocula. For controlled environment assays, surface sterilized seeds were inoculated with log 6 Bacillus or log 8 Pseudomonas colony-forming units (cfu) under gnotobiotic conditions for assessment of rhizosphere and internal root and stem tissue colonization. In the Æeld trial, one-yearold, container-grown hybrid spruce seedlings were inoculated with each of the Bacillus or Pseudomonas strains 1±2 days before planting at nine Æeld sites in British Columbia and Alberta, Canada. All six strains colonized the rhizosphere with log 5.6ˇ7.6 cfu gˇ1 root tissue under controlled environmental conditions. Two strains, Bacillus Pw-2R and Pseudomonas Sm3RN, were also recovered from internal root and stem tissues with population sizes ranging from log 3.9 to log 5.0 cfu gˇ1 plant tissue. In the Æeld trial, PGPR survived the winter in the rhizosphere with populations of log 2 to log 5 cfu gˇ1 root tissue 17 months after inoculation. In addition, spruce growth was signiÆcantly enhanced by bacterial inoculation at certain sites. The most effective growth-promoting strains were the endophytes, Sm3-RN and Pw2-R, and the external root colonizing strain, Ss2-RN. These three strains increased seedling dry weight up to 57% above noninoculated controls at Æve of the nine outplanting sites. Pseudomonas strain Sw1 and the other two Bacillus strains produced mean spruce dry weight increases at four of the sites. Seedling growth inhibition due to bacterial inoculation was detected at some sites. Our results conÆrm the short-term, site speciÆc effectiveness of PGPR for reforestation of conifer seedlings, and indicate that beneÆts of a single inoculation at planting can extend through the second year in the Æeld. In addition, bacteria capable of colonizing the seedling interior may be more effective PGPR for spruce than those restricted to the rhizosphere and the root surface. However, site speciÆc seedling growth promotion may necessitate matching PGPR strains to outplanting sites for effective growth promotion. # 2000 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.
